        <h2><a><i class="icon icon-cogs"></i> Graph Visualization</a></h2>
        <p class="lead">Storing a graph is one thing, but visualizing it creates awe and epiphanies</p>
      </div>

    <p>Graph visualisations are a powerful tool to convey the content of a graph. They can highlight patterns, show clusters and connections.
    </p>

    <p>There are different tools that you can use to visualize the content of a Neo4j graph database.</p>
    <h3>Neo4j Server Web Interface</h3>

      <p>The Data Browser Tab offers a handy visualization of your graph. You can select the nodes to be shown by id,  index lookup or <a href="/learn/cypher">cypher query</a>. A style editor will adapt the visualization to your needs.</p>
      <p>The Neo4j Server Web Interface was written using arbor.js and canvas.

      <img width="500" align="Neo4j Server Visualization" src="/assets/img/still/server_visualization.jpg"/>

    <h3>Neoclipse</h3>
      <p>Neoclipse is a <a href="https://github.com/neo4j/neoclipse/blob/master/README.asciidoc" target="_blank">standalone desktop app</a> (written in eclipse RCP) which allows to connect to a Neo4j Database directory or a running Neo4j Server
      to visualize the content of the graph. It allows filtering of relationships and properties, has different layout modes, and supports Cypher and index queries.</p>
      
      <iframe src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/12014944?badge=0&byline=0&portrait=0&title=0" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>

      <h3>JavaScript D3.js</h3>

      <p>D3 is the most powerful javascrip visualization library which supports a large number of visualizations, many of them are usable for graphs as well, <a href="http://maxdemarzi.com/tag/visualization-2/" target="_blank">Max De Marzi</a> covered several of the visualizations on his blog.</p>

      <img width="500" align="D3 visualization example" src="/assets/img/still/d3_network.png"/>
      
      <h3>Gephi</h3>

        <p>The well known Graph visualization tool Gephi has a <a href="http://gephi.org/tag/neo4j/" target="_blank">plugin for importing Neo4j</a> Databases which can then be visualized and rendered with the full power of Gephi&#39;s engines.</p>

      <iframe src="http://player.vimeo.com/video/31823202?badge=0&byline=0&portrait=0&title=0" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe>

      <h3>GraphViz</h3>

      <p>Using the GraphViz Exporter it is possible to generate <code>.dot</code> files which can then be rendered as images using graphviz&#39; dot toolchain.

      See this <a href="http://blog.neo4j.org/2012/05/graph-this-rendering-your-graph-with.html" target="_blank">blog post</a> for details.</p>

